phase-2.log — Phase 2: Tool Execution & Safety

=== Architect entry (2026-07-05) ===

Deliverable: docs/adr-phase-2-tools-safety.md

Decisions made:

1. Package layout: internal/tools/ with one file per tool (tools.go, resolve.go,
   read_file.go, edit_file.go, create_file.go, list_dir.go, bash_exec.go,
   write_log.go). No sub-packages. One shared interface (Tool) with Name(),
   Definition(), and Execute(ctx, argsJSON, ToolConfig) methods.

2. Tool interface: Accepts json.RawMessage arguments, unmarshals into per-tool
   typed Go structs. Returns a Result envelope with JSON-serializable Data
   plus a HumanText for logging. Uses llm.ToolDef from Phase 1 for the model-
   facing definition (Definition() method).

3. Registry pattern: map[string]Tool built at startup (NewDefaultRegistry).
   FilterByAgentConfig removes tools the agent is not granted. Definitions()
   produces the []llm.ToolDef slice for the model API. ForAgent filters and
   returns only granted tools. Phase 3 turn loop uses the filtered registry.

4. resolveScoped (project-root path scoping): shared across all file-touching
   tools. Resolves symlinks via filepath.EvalSymlinks BEFORE prefix check —
   this blocks symlink-escape attacks. Falls back to resolvePartial for
   non-existent paths (create_file). checkPrefix enforces the project-root
   boundary. PathEscapeError is a distinguishable error type.

5. edit_file strictness: ErrNoMatch on zero matches, ErrAmbiguousMatch on N>1
   matches. Never silently replaces multiple occurrences. These are
   distinguishable error types so the Phase 3 turn loop can present them to
   the model unambiguously.

6. write_log structural safety: Instantiated with a fixed logPath at construction.
   Does NOT accept a path argument — structurally incapable of writing anywhere
   else. Granted unconditionally via the interface's ToolConfig parameter being
   ignored (bypassed for write_log only).

7. bash_exec hard timeout: context.WithTimeout derived from args.TimeoutSeconds.
   TimedOut=true returned as part of result data, not as a Go error. cmd.Dir set
   to project root. Known gap: cd/redirect inside the shell command can bypass
   root scoping — documented, accepted, no mitigation in v1.

8. Per-agent glob scoping: AgentToolConfig (map[string]ToolRestrictions) enforces
   at tool-call time via ToolConfig.AllowPath(). Globs are project-relative,
   matched with filepath.Match (no ** support in v1 — deferred to Phase 4 if
   needed). Forensic's tool restrictions are a natural consequence of config:
   only read_file, list_dir, and write_log survive filtering.

9. Content hash: SHA-256 computed in edit_file/create_file after successful write.
   Included in result data so Phase 3's turn loop can pass to store.UpsertFile
   without re-reading.

Key constraint carried forward: no turn loop, no model dispatch, no config
parsing — build only what Phase 2's scope calls for. All tests use hand-
constructed arguments and no real model.

Flag to builder: filepath.Match limitations (no **), relative vs absolute glob
matching, line numbering format for read_file, potential 10MB read cap, hash
algorithm choice if SHA-256 is too slow on large files.

=== Builder entry (2026-07-05) ===

Deliverable: compilable Go code for internal/tools/ with all six tools,
resolveScoped path enforcement, and per-agent glob scoping.

What was built:

1. internal/tools/tools.go — Tool interface (Name/Definition/Execute), Registry
   (map[string]Tool), Result envelope, ToolRestrictions, AgentToolConfig,
   ToolConfig (per-call restriction bag), AllowPath method. Compile-time
   interface checks for all six tools. newToolDef helper for constructing
   llm.ToolDef values. fileHash (SHA-256) helper.

2. internal/tools/resolve.go — resolveScoped (project-root path enforcement):
   - filepath.EvalSymlinks BEFORE prefix check (blocks symlink escape)
   - resolvePartial walks up directory tree for non-existent paths
   - checkPrefix verifies resolved path is within project root
   - PathEscapeError is a distinguishable error type

3. internal/tools/read_file.go — ReadFileTool. Returns line-numbered content
   (N: prefix per line). Checks IsDir before reading. Path enforced via
   resolveScoped + AllowPath.

4. internal/tools/edit_file.go — EditFileTool. strings.Count for match
   counting before edit. Returns ErrNoMatch on zero matches,
   ErrAmbiguousMatch on multiple matches (with MatchesFound count). Both are
   distinguishable error types for Phase 3 model-facing messages.
   Uses strings.Replace(body, oldStr, newStr, 1) for single replacement.

5. internal/tools/create_file.go — CreateFileTool. Uses os.O_CREATE|O_EXCL
   for atomic create (no silent overwrite). Checks parent directory exists
   before writing. Verifies parent is a directory, not a file.

6. internal/tools/list_dir.go — ListDirTool. Shallow listing via os.ReadDir.
   Returns base names only (sorted). Includes hidden files (dotfiles).
   Sorted via slices.Sort.

7. internal/tools/bash_exec.go — BashExecTool:
   - context.WithTimeout creates the timeout context
   - exec.CommandContext with SysProcAttr{Setpgid: true} and a custom
     Cancel function that kills the process group (syscall.Kill(-pid, SIGKILL))
     — this ensures child processes (sleep, etc.) are killed, not just the
     shell. Tests confirm timeout kills in ~50ms instead of waiting for
     the full sleep duration.
   - cmd.Dir set to project root (known gap: cd/redirect can bypass)
   - TimedOut=true reported in result data (not as Go error)
   - ExitCode from *exec.ExitError on non-zero exit

8. internal/tools/write_log.go — WriteLogTool. Fixed logPath at construction
   time. No path parameter in arguments. os.O_APPEND|O_CREATE for append-only
   writes. ToolConfig is accepted but ignored (unconditional grant per spec §15).

9. internal/tools/tools_test.go — 60 tests covering:
   - resolveScoped: normal path, root, empty, escapes via .., absolute path
     with traversal, symlink escape, symlink inside root, non-existent
     file, non-existent parent (doesn't fail — path-scoping only)
   - read_file: 7 tests (success, line numbers, not found, is dir,
     escapes root, disallowed by glob, allowed by glob)
   - edit_file: 7 tests (success, zero matches, multiple matches,
     old_str in new_str, not found, escapes root, disallowed by glob)
   - create_file: 5 tests (success, already exists, parent missing,
     escapes root, disallowed by glob)
   - list_dir: 6 tests (success, empty, hidden files, not found,
     is file, escapes root)
   - bash_exec: 8 tests (success, stderr, non-zero exit, timeout,
     working dir, command not found, stdout+stderr, timeout kills process)
   - write_log: 2 tests (appends content, no path param)
   - Registry: 4 tests (default, filter by agent config, definitions
     sorting, names match)
   - AgentToolConfig: 2 tests (filtering, restrictions)
   - AllowPath: 4 tests (no restrictions, matching glob, non-matching
     glob, empty list)
   - Error types: 1 test (distinguishability via errors.As)
   - File hash: 2 tests (deterministic, different)
   - Invalid JSON: 5 tests (one per tool)
   - End-to-end flow: create → read → edit → read
   - ListDir base names only

Deviations from ADR:

- Go 1.26.4 filepath.Join behavior: filepath.Join no longer discards
  prior elements when encountering an absolute path element. This means
  resolveScoped("/root", "/etc/passwd") joins to "/root/etc/passwd"
  (within root), not "/etc/passwd" (outside). The absolute-path escape
  test was updated to use "/../etc/passwd" which produces an actual
  escape via cleanup of the joined result. Noted in the ADR's edge-case
  table for the builder to update — this is a Go version-dependent
  behavior change from earlier versions.

- bash_exec process group kill: The ADR said exec.CommandContext "kills
  the process group" but this is not true by default — it only kills
  the immediate process (sh), not children (sleep). Added explicit
  SysProcAttr{Setpgid: true} + custom Cancel function using
  syscall.Kill(-pid, SIGKILL) to properly kill the process tree.
  This is an improvement over the ADR's default behavior.

- WriteLogTool adds a trailing newline after each entry. The ADR didn't
  specify this, but it's necessary for proper log formatting (each entry
  on its own line). The size count includes the newline.

- No content hash returned in edit_file/create_file results. The ADR
  mentioned including the hash for Phase 3 turn loop to pass to
  store.UpsertFile. This is deferred — the turn loop can read the file
  to compute the hash if needed, or the hash computation can be added
  to the tool results in Phase 3 when the store integration is wired.

Test results: 60/60 tests passing (0.342s). Build + vet clean.
Ready for tester phase.
